 """
 Stage 3 — Critic: validates LLM-generated fields for claim/evidence fidelity.
 
-Two layers:
-1. Deterministic checks (no LLM): quotes (substring), year range, theme vocab, geocoding
-2. LLM critic (Sonnet): per-claim evidence verification for summary, themes, location,
-   alternatives, historical context
+Three layers:
+  1. Deterministic hard gates (no LLM): quotes (substring), year range,
+     theme vocab, geocoding. Always run regardless of budget.
+  2. Self-consistency / cross-field checks (small, deterministic).
+  3. Tiered LLM critic:
+       - Haiku tier: presence/format checks on title, year, eis_type,
+         lead_agency.name, alternative names.
+       - Sonnet tier: grounded reasoning on summary, alternative
+         descriptions, stance + quote, themes, location, historical_internal.
+       - Opus tier: binding retry when Sonnet returns "no" on a field that
+         would otherwise block ship. Capped per doc by
+         OPUS_RETRY_BUDGET_PER_DOC.
+
+Under critic-stage budget pressure (running per-doc cost >
+CRITIC_BUDGET_PER_DOC_USD partway through Layer 3), tiers are shed in order
+Opus → Sonnet → Haiku. Skipped fields get verdict="skipped",
+tier="skipped_budget_cap". Pydantic + Layers 1+2 always run.
+
+Verdict semantics:
+  - "pass"    — no change.
+  - "partial" — field value kept; review_status downgraded if it changes
+                the auto-approve gate.
+  - "no"      — field value kept on the schema (so consumers don't lose
+                data), but for summary / historical_internal we preserve the
+                pre-existing behavior of downgrading their status field to
+                "insufficient_information".
 """
 
